`crates/steno/src/expand` turns parsed AST entries into fully-typed, terminal-flagged `TypedEntry` records ready for rendering. It's the pipeline stage between parsing and code generation: callers get `expand_dict` and see none of the intermediate per-pass structure.

The pipeline is a strict four-stage sequence, each stage's output shape constraining the next: `expand_counts` (Pass A, counts.rs) resolves `%d`/`%(EXPR)`/`%[...]` but deliberately leaves `%t`/`%b`/braces/landings untouched, producing `ExpandedEntry`; `expand_types_one` (Pass B, append.rs) consumes that and fills `%t` slots using `fill.rs`'s substitution primitives and `types.rs`'s `TypeDef`/`TypeOptions` type pool, producing `TypedEntry` with per-entry terminality; `fix_family_terminals` (family.rs) then corrects terminality across the *whole batch* (a stroke that's a strict prefix of another is never terminal) — this must run after all entries are typed, not per-entry; finally `expand_line_flag` (lineflag.rs) doubles eligible multi-stroke terminal entries into one-liner variants by adding `U` to the *first* stroke segment. Order matters throughout: family-fixup needs Pass B's terminal flags on the full set, and line-flag needs family-fixup's corrected terminality.

`types.rs` and `fill.rs` are the shared type-machinery layer underneath append.rs: `types.rs` builds the `TypeSet`/`arity0` pool from `@type` entries (enforcing that `@type` templates contain only `Lit`/`TypeSlot` chunks), and `fill.rs` enumerates append chains (`Filling`) and does the actual `%t` substitution, including the free-type (`SKP`) path that emits a `Chunk::Landing` tabstop instead of literal text — a convention `infinite/`'s `walk.rs` must independently replicate to keep its replay path in sync.

Cross-cutting invariant: only `fix_family_terminals` may flip `terminal` `true`→`false`; no other stage sets it after Pass B. Stroke text is always `/`-joined and each pass here treats the last segment specially (count-bank merge in counts.rs, fuse-merge in append.rs) — that segment-position convention is shared, not restated per file.

`infinite/` is a sibling replay implementation of Pass B's fill/terminal semantics for a different dictionary-generation strategy; it must track this directory's `%t`/fuse/terminal conventions but does not depend on it directly.